<title>BELGIUM: Romanians most hot on EU-NATO membership.</title>
<headline>Romanians most hot on EU-NATO membership.</headline>
<dateline>BRUSSELS 1997-03-25</dateline>
<text>
<p>Romanians are the people in central and eastern Europe most desperate to join the European Union and NATO, a study prepared by the European Commission revealed on Tuesday.</p>
<p>The Eurobarometer poll of more than 20,000 people in 20 countries showed that 80 percent of Romanians favour EU membership, and 76 percent membership of the North Atlantic Treaty Organisation military alliance.</p>
<p>Closely behind is Poland, where 70 percent favour membership of the EU and 65 percent want membership of NATO.</p>
<p>The people interviewed in the Baltic States -- Estonia, Latvia and Lithuana -- on the other hand stood out as against membership of the EU, with only a quarter saying they had a positive image of the EU.</p>
<p>The poll shows however, that while all except the Baltic countries favour EU membership, only Romania, Poland and Estonia are enthusiastic about joining NATO.</p>
<p>&quot;Although there is no absolute majority against NATO membership in any country the large number of indecideds creates a cloud of uncertainty concerning how any future referenda may turn out,&quot; Eurobarometer said.</p>
<p>The poll shows that two out of five people across the 20 countries see their future increasingly linked with Europe, while only 17 percent favour closer ties with the United States.</p>
<p>People in the Baltic State of Latvia on the other hand see their future linked to Russia. Russians themselves see the future of their country linked with the United States and with other countries of the Commonwealth of Independent States.</p>
<p>The countries covered in the poll are Estonia, Romania, the Czech Republic, Slovakia, Poland, Slovenia, Lithuania, Latvia, Hungary, Bulgaria, Albania, Yugoslavia and Croatia, the former Yugoslav republic of Macedonia, Georgia, Armenia, Belarus, Russia, Kazakhstan and the Ukraine.</p>
